  "output": "## What this codebase actually is\n\n`jobsquare` is a Python CLI/batch pipeline (fetch → filter → dedup → notify), not a web app — there's no React or frontend code anywhere in the repo, so \"re-render\" analysis doesn't apply. I'm reporting only what's actually verifiable in `store.py`, `filters.py`, `fetchers.py`, `agent.py`.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (store.py:55-74)\n\nReal and the highest-impact finding. For every job in the batch (boards like Microsoft/Amazon/Apple/Google are explicitly documented as \"thousands of roles,\" capped at hundreds via `max_pages`), it issues one `SELECT` to check existence, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nWith a few thousand jobs per run this is thousands of individual round-trips through SQLite's VM instead of one. Fix — load the existing key→hash map once, diff in Python, and batch the no-op `last_seen` touches:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = {r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"]\n                for r in self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\")}\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(1) reads + batched writes. The jobs table is small enough (tens of thousands of rows at most for a personal tracker) to load entirely into memory safely.\n\nRelated, smaller: `Job.content_hash` (a SHA-256 over title/location/url/department) is computed once in the diff comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and then recomputed inside `to_row()` when `_update`/`_insert` runs. Cheap per-call, but redundant at scale — worth passing the already-computed hash through instead of recomputing.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:_compile()` recompiled per job\n\n`filter_jobs()` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` on *every single call* (filters.py:11-27):\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every job!\n```\n\n`sources.yaml` has 4 include + 5 exclude keywords; with ~2-5k jobs fetched per run (Microsoft alone allows `max_pages=40` × 10/page), that's up to ~45,000 `re.compile()` calls doing pure repeated work on identical patterns. Fix — compile once, outside the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                       locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\nand change `match()` to accept pre-compiled `list[re.Pattern]` directly instead of raw keyword lists.\n\n## 3. Missing index — `store.py:added_since()`\n\n```python\n\"SELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title\"\n```\nThere's an index on `company` (store.py:27) but none on `first_seen`, which is exactly the column this query filters and sorts by — every `agent.py db-new` call (used by the scan mode) does a full table scan. Add:\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n## 4. Caching opportunity — no HTTP conditional requests\n\nNone of the ~19 fetchers in `fetchers.py` use `ETag`/`If-Modified-Since`. Every scheduled run (the repo runs on a 12h cron per the recent commit) does a full fetch of every configured board even when nothing changed. Several ATS endpoints (Greenhouse, Lever, SmartRecruiters) support standard HTTP caching headers. This mainly matters for reducing load on third-party APIs and speeding up dev iteration, not correctness — local dedup already happens via `content_hash` — but a simple per-URL `ETag` cache in `_request()`/`_get_json()` would cut bandwidth and avoid unnecessary work on unchanged boards.\n\n## 5. Memory leaks — none found\n\nThis is a short-lived batch CLI, not a long-running server, so classic leak patterns (unbounded caches, unclosed listeners, growing global state) don't apply. Resource lifecycle is handled correctly: `Store` closes via context manager (`pipeline.py:42`), `httpx.AsyncClient` closes in `finally` (`fetchers.py:1144-1146`), SMTP connection closes via context manager (`notify.py:69`). One minor note: raw ATS payloads (`raw=j`) are held in memory for every `Job` in the batch simultaneously until `to_row()` drops them at DB-write time — not a leak, just peak-memory overhead that's already been consciously trimmed for Google (`fetchers.py:313-314` comment explicitly avoids holding full HTML descriptions). Not worth changing at current job-volume scale.\n\n## Priority order\n1. `Store.diff()` batch query (#1) — biggest real win, straightforward fix.\n2. `filters.py` regex precompilation (#2) — cheap fix, pure waste eliminated.\n3. `first_seen` index (#3) — one-line schema addition.\n4. HTTP caching (#4) — optional, only matters if you want to be a better API citizen or speed up local dev.\n",
